      <div class="pwn-bar" style="background:var(--neuro-r)"></div>
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="pw-detail" id="audi-pathway-detail">
    <h4>Cochlear Nuclei (Medulla)</h4>
    <p>First CNS synapse. The cochlear nerve synapses here in the dorsal and ventral cochlear nuclei in the medulla. Encodes frequency, intensity, and timing cues. Projections from here both <strong>cross (decussate)</strong> via the trapezoid body and ascend ipsilaterally — giving rise to the bilateral nature of central auditory processing.</p>
  </div>

  <div class="two-col flip">
    <div class="info-panel">
      <div class="info-intro">
        The central auditory pathway has <strong>six main relay stations</strong> between the cochlea and the cortex. This bilateral organization is why a unilateral cortical lesion rarely causes profound hearing loss — the other hemisphere still receives input.
      </div>
      <div class="accordion-item">
        <button class="accordion-btn" onclick="toggleAcc(this)">
          <span><span class="acc-label" style="background:rgba(123,63,140,.1);color:var(--neuro-r)">Cortex</span>Wernicke's Area — Comprehension</span>
          <span class="acc-icon">▼</span>
        </button>
        <div class="accordion-body"><div class="accordion-body-inner"><ul>
          <li><strong>Location:</strong> Posterior superior temporal gyrus, Brodmann area 22, left hemisphere</li>
          <li>Decodes the linguistic content of incoming speech — recognizes "Do you like cheese?" as a yes/no question requiring a spoken response</li>
          <li><strong>Wernicke's aphasia</strong> (if damaged): fluent but meaningless speech; severely impaired comprehension</li>
          <li>Connects to Broca's area via the <strong>arcuate fasciculus</strong> — the white matter bundle that links comprehension to production</li>
        </ul></div></div>
      </div>
      <div class="accordion-item">
        <button class="accordion-btn" onclick="toggleAcc(this)">
          <span><span class="acc-label" style="background:rgba(123,63,140,.1);color:var(--neuro-r)">CN</span>Key Cranial Nerves for Reception</span>
          <span class="acc-icon">▼</span>
        </button>
        <div class="accordion-body"><div class="accordion-body-inner"><ul>
          <li><strong>CN VIII (Vestibulocochlear):</strong> Carries the acoustic signal from the cochlea to the brainstem — the sole afferent nerve for hearing</li>
          <li><strong>CN VII (Facial):</strong> Motor to stapedius muscle — mediates the acoustic reflex protecting hearing at high intensities</li>
          <li><strong>CN V (Trigeminal):</strong> Motor to tensor tympani — secondary acoustic reflex muscle</li>
        </ul></div></div>
      </div>
      <a class="next-link" href="#neuro-formulate" style="border-color:var(--neuro-f);color:var(--neuro-f)">
        <div><span class="nl-label">Next →</span>Neurological System: Formulating a Response</div>
        <span class="nl-arrow">→</span>
      </a>
    </div>
    <div>
      <div class="diagram-wrap" id="diag-neuro-r">
        <div class="diagram-img-area" id="diag-neuro-r-img">
          <div class="diagram-placeholder">
            <div style="font-size:2.5rem">🧠</div>
            <strong style="font-size:.8rem">REPLACE WITH YOUR IMAGE</strong>
            <span>Suggested: Brain lateral view showing<br/>Wernicke's area + auditory cortex labeled</span>
          </div>
          <div class="hotspot" style="left:55%;top:30%;color:var(--neuro-r);background:var(--neuro-r)" data-popup="hs-nr-1" title="Primary Auditory Cortex">A1</div>
          <div class="hotspot" style="left:72%;top:48%;color:var(--neuro-r);background:var(--neuro-r)" data-popup="hs-nr-2" title="Wernicke's Area">W</div>
          <div class="hotspot" style="left:40%;top:55%;color:var(--neuro-r);background:var(--neuro-r)" data-popup="hs-nr-3" title="Arcuate Fasciculus">AF</div>
        </div>
        <div class="hs-popup" id="hs-nr-1">
          <button class="pop-close" onclick="closePopup('hs-nr-1')">✕</button>
          <div class="pop-label"><span class="pop-accent" style="background:var(--neuro-r)"></span>Cortex</div>
          <h4>Primary Auditory Cortex (A1)</h4>
          <p>Located on Heschl's gyrus (transverse temporal gyrus), Brodmann areas 41 &amp; 42, in the superior temporal plane. Tonotopically organized — different regions respond to different frequencies. Receives primarily contralateral input. Processes basic acoustic features (frequency, intensity, timing) of "Do you like cheese?"</p>
        </div>
        <div class="hs-popup" id="hs-nr-2">
          <button class="pop-close" onclick="closePopup('hs-nr-2')">✕</button>
          <div class="pop-label"><span class="pop-accent" style="background:var(--neuro-r)"></span>Language Cortex</div>
          <h4>Wernicke's Area (BA 22)</h4>
          <p>The posterior superior temporal gyrus — the key area for <strong>language comprehension</strong>. After A1 processes the acoustic features, Wernicke's area assigns linguistic meaning. It recognizes "Do you like cheese?" as a question about cheese preference, triggering the need for a verbal response. Damage here causes Wernicke's aphasia.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="hs-popup" id="hs-nr-3">
          <button class="pop-close" onclick="closePopup('hs-nr-3')">✕</button>
          <div class="pop-label"><span class="pop-accent" style="background:var(--neuro-r)"></span>White Matter Tract</div>
          <h4>Arcuate Fasciculus</h4>
          <p>A critical white matter bundle that connects Wernicke's area (comprehension) to Broca's area (motor speech production). After understanding the question, this tract carries the linguistic information forward to Broca's area so a spoken response can be planned. Damage causes <strong>conduction aphasia</strong> — impaired repetition with relatively preserved comprehension and fluency.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="diagram-caption">Fig. 2 — Cortical language areas (left hemisphere). Click hotspots to explore.</div>
