<!-- ══════════════════════════════════════
     03 — NEURO: FORMULATING
══════════════════════════════════════ -->
<section id="neuro-formulate" class="system-section sec-neuro-f">
  <div class="sys-header">
    <div class="sys-step-tag">Step 03 · The Brain Plans the Response</div>
    <h2 class="sys-title">Neurological System:<br/>Formulating &amp; Motor Planning</h2>
    <p class="sys-subtitle">Once the question is understood, the brain must formulate a reply, create a motor speech program, and send descending commands to the muscles of respiration, phonation, and articulation.</p>
  </div>

  <div class="two-col">
    <div>
      <div class="diagram-wrap" id="diag-neuro-f">
        <div class="diagram-img-area">
          <div class="diagram-placeholder">
            <div style="font-size:2.5rem">🧠</div>
            <strong style="font-size:.8rem">REPLACE WITH YOUR IMAGE</strong>
            <span>Suggested: Brain showing Broca's area,<br/>motor cortex, basal ganglia, cerebellum</span>
          </div>
          <div class="hotspot" style="left:28%;top:35%;color:var(--neuro-f);background:var(--neuro-f)" data-popup="hs-nf-1" title="Broca's Area">B</div>
          <div class="hotspot" style="left:48%;top:22%;color:var(--neuro-f);background:var(--neuro-f)" data-popup="hs-nf-2" title="Motor Cortex">M</div>
          <div class="hotspot" style="left:52%;top:55%;color:var(--neuro-f);background:var(--neuro-f)" data-popup="hs-nf-3" title="Basal Ganglia">BG</div>
          <div class="hotspot" style="left:70%;top:70%;color:var(--neuro-f);background:var(--neuro-f)" data-popup="hs-nf-4" title="Cerebellum">CB</div>
        </div>
        <div class="hs-popup" id="hs-nf-1">
          <button class="pop-close" onclick="closePopup('hs-nf-1')">✕</button>
          <div class="pop-label"><span class="pop-accent" style="background:var(--neuro-f)"></span>Motor Speech Programming</div>
          <h4>Broca's Area (BA 44 &amp; 45)</h4>
          <p>The inferior frontal gyrus of the left hemisphere. After Wernicke's area comprehends the question, Broca's area formulates the <strong>motor speech program</strong> — the precise sequence of articulatory gestures, phonemes, and prosodic patterns needed to say "Yes, I love cheese!" Damage causes Broca's aphasia: non-fluent, effortful, telegraphic speech with relatively preserved comprehension.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="hs-popup" id="hs-nf-2">
          <button class="pop-close" onclick="closePopup('hs-nf-2')">✕</button>
          <div class="pop-label"><span class="pop-accent" style="background:var(--neuro-f)"></span>Motor Execution</div>
          <h4>Primary Motor Cortex</h4>
          <p>The precentral gyrus executes the motor program from Broca's area. It sends commands via the <strong>corticobulbar tract</strong> to cranial nerve motor nuclei in the brainstem (controlling laryngeal, orofacial, and velopharyngeal muscles) and via the <strong>corticospinal tract</strong> to the spinal cord (controlling respiratory muscles). This is where the abstract speech plan becomes physical muscle activation.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="hs-popup" id="hs-nf-3">
          <button class="pop-close" onclick="closePopup('hs-nf-3')">✕</button>
          <div class="pop-label"><span class="pop-accent" style="background:var(--neuro-f)"></span>Extrapyramidal System</div>
          <h4>Basal Ganglia</h4>
          <p>A group of subcortical nuclei (caudate nucleus, putamen, globus pallidus, subthalamic nucleus, substantia nigra) that regulate movement <strong>automaticity, muscle tone</strong>, and suppression of unwanted movements. Dopaminergic pathways from the substantia nigra are essential. Disruption → <strong>hypokinetic dysarthria</strong> (Parkinson's disease) or <strong>hyperkinetic dysarthria</strong> (Huntington's disease).</p>
        </div>
        <div class="hs-popup" id="hs-nf-4">
          <button class="pop-close" onclick="closePopup('hs-nf-4')">✕</button>
          <div class="pop-label"><span class="pop-accent" style="background:var(--neuro-f)"></span>Coordination Center</div>
          <h4>Cerebellum</h4>
          <p>The cerebellum compares the <strong>intended movement</strong> (efference copy from motor cortex) against the <strong>actual movement</strong> (proprioceptive/tactile feedback) and corrects errors in real time. It coordinates timing, rhythm, and precision. Cerebellar damage → <strong>ataxic dysarthria</strong>: irregular, scanning speech with breakdowns in articulatory coordination.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="diagram-caption">Fig. 3 — Motor speech planning areas. Click hotspots to explore.</div>
        <div class="diagram-hint"><div class="pulse-dot-hint" style="--accent:var(--neuro-f)"></div> Click the glowing circles to learn about each area</div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="info-panel">
      <div class="info-intro">
        The motor speech system involves <strong>three parallel neural loops</strong>: the pyramidal (direct voluntary control), the extrapyramidal (automaticity and tone), and the cerebellar (timing and error correction). All three work together for every spoken utterance.
      </div>
      <div class="accordion-item">
        <button class="accordion-btn" onclick="toggleAcc(this)">
          <span><span class="acc-label" style="background:rgba(61,90,142,.1);color:var(--neuro-f)">Direct</span>Pyramidal System</span>
          <span class="acc-icon">▼</span>
        </button>
        <div class="accordion-body"><div class="accordion-body-inner"><ul>
          <li><strong>Corticobulbar tract:</strong> Motor cortex → cranial nerve nuclei (brainstem) → speech muscles of larynx, face, tongue, palate</li>
          <li><strong>Corticospinal tract:</strong> Motor cortex → spinal anterior horn → respiratory muscles (diaphragm, intercostals, abdominals)</li>
          <li>Controls fine, voluntary, rapid movements; UMN damage → <strong>spastic dysarthria</strong></li>
        </ul></div></div>
      </div>
      <div class="accordion-item">
        <button class="accordion-btn" onclick="toggleAcc(this)">
          <span><span class="acc-label" style="background:rgba(61,90,142,.1);color:var(--neuro-f)">Key CNs</span>Cranial Nerves for Speech Production</span>
          <span class="acc-icon">▼</span>
        </button>
        <div class="accordion-body"><div class="accordion-body-inner"><ul>
          <li><strong>CN V (Trigeminal):</strong> Jaw muscles — masseter, temporalis, pterygoids</li>
          <li><strong>CN VII (Facial):</strong> All lip muscles — orbicularis oris, buccinator, zygomaticus</li>
          <li><strong>CN X (Vagus):</strong> All intrinsic laryngeal muscles (RLN), pharyngeal constrictors, levator veli palatini</li>
          <li><strong>CN XII (Hypoglossal):</strong> All intrinsic and most extrinsic tongue muscles</li>
          <li><strong>CN XI (Accessory):</strong> SCM and trapezius — head posture for speech</li>
        </ul></div></div>
      </div>
      <a class="next-link" href="#respiratory" style="border-color:var(--resp);color:var(--resp)">
        <div><span class="nl-label">Next →</span>Respiratory System — the power source activates</div>
        <span class="nl-arrow">→</span>
      </a>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- ══════════════════════════════════════
     04 — RESPIRATORY
══════════════════════════════════════ -->
<section id="respiratory" class="system-section sec-resp" style="background:var(--surface2)">
  <div class="sys-header">
    <div class="sys-step-tag">Step 04 · The Airstream is Generated</div>
    <h2 class="sys-title">Respiratory System</h2>
    <p class="sys-subtitle">The motor cortex triggers the respiratory muscles to take a quick, large inhalation and then regulate a slow, controlled exhalation — generating the subglottal air pressure that powers all speech.</p>
  </div>

  <div class="two-col flip">
    <div class="info-panel">
      <div class="info-intro">
        Speech breathing differs dramatically from life breathing. A quick inhalation of <strong>20–60% of vital capacity</strong> is followed by a slow, actively controlled exhalation across the entire utterance, maintaining <strong>~7–10 cm H₂O</strong> of subglottal pressure.
      </div>
      <div class="accordion-item">
        <button class="accordion-btn" onclick="toggleAcc(this)">
          <span><span class="acc-label" style="background:rgba(46,125,94,.1);color:var(--resp)">Physics</span>Boyle's Law &amp; Breathing Mechanics</span>
          <span class="acc-icon">▼</span>
        </button>
        <div class="accordion-body"><div class="accordion-body-inner"><ul>
          <li><strong>Boyle's Law (P₁V₁ = P₂V₂):</strong> Volume ↑ → Pressure ↓ → Air flows in (inspiration)</li>
          <li><strong>Inspiration:</strong> Diaphragm contracts → thorax expands → intrapulmonary P drops below atmospheric → air in</li>
          <li><strong>Expiration for speech:</strong> Abdominal muscles actively compress → intrapulmonary P rises → controlled airflow out</li>
          <li><strong>Checking action:</strong> Inspiratory muscles resist elastic recoil early in the utterance; expiratory muscles generate force later</li>
        </ul></div></div>
      </div>
      <div class="accordion-item">
        <button class="accordion-btn" onclick="toggleAcc(this)">
          <span><span class="acc-label" style="background:rgba(46,125,94,.1);color:var(--resp)">Muscles</span>Inspiration &amp; Expiration</span>
          <span class="acc-icon">▼</span>
        </button>
        <div class="accordion-body"><div class="accordion-body-inner"><ul>
          <li><strong>Diaphragm (CN: Phrenic, C3–C5):</strong> Primary inspiratory muscle; flattens to increase vertical thoracic dimension</li>
          <li><strong>External intercostals:</strong> Elevate ribs; increase anteroposterior + transverse dimensions</li>
          <li><strong>Transversus abdominis:</strong> Deepest abdominal; key for sustained speech pressure regulation</li>
          <li><strong>Rectus abdominis:</strong> Compresses abdomen; raises diaphragm for forceful expiration</li>
          <li><strong>Internal oblique &amp; External oblique:</strong> Compress abdominal contents during speech</li>
        </ul></div></div>
      </div>
      <div class="accordion-item">
        <button class="accordion-btn" onclick="toggleAcc(this)">
          <span><span class="acc-label" style="background:rgba(46,125,94,.1);color:var(--resp)">Volumes</span>Lung Volumes &amp; Capacities</span>
          <span class="acc-icon">▼</span>
        </button>
        <div class="accordion-body"><div class="accordion-body-inner"><ul>
          <li><strong>Tidal Volume (TV):</strong> ~500 mL — normal resting breath</li>
          <li><strong>Inspiratory Reserve Volume (IRV):</strong> ~3,000 mL — additional inhale beyond TV</li>
          <li><strong>Expiratory Reserve Volume (ERV):</strong> ~1,100 mL — additional forceful exhale</li>
          <li><strong>Residual Volume (RV):</strong> ~1,200 mL — cannot be expelled</li>
          <li><strong>Vital Capacity (VC):</strong> ~4,600 mL = IRV + TV + ERV</li>
          <li><strong>Speech uses:</strong> 20–60% VC vs. only ~10% VC for quiet breathing</li>
        </ul></div></div>
      </div>
