<section id="phonatory" class="system-section sec-phon">
  <div class="sys-header">
    <div class="sys-step-tag">Step 05 · The Voice is Produced</div>
    <h2 class="sys-title">Phonatory System</h2>
    <p class="sys-subtitle">The airstream from the lungs reaches the larynx, where the vocal folds adduct and begin vibrating — converting aerodynamic energy into acoustic energy (sound) via the Myoelastic-Aerodynamic Theory.</p>
  </div>

  <div class="two-col">
    <div>
      <div class="diagram-wrap">
        <div class="diagram-img-area">
          <div class="diagram-placeholder">
            <div style="font-size:2.5rem">〰️</div>
            <strong style="font-size:.8rem">REPLACE WITH YOUR IMAGE</strong>
            <span>Suggested: Labeled laryngeal diagram<br/>showing cartilages + vocal folds (superior view)</span>
          </div>
          <div class="hotspot" style="left:50%;top:18%;color:var(--phon);background:var(--phon)" data-popup="hs-ph-1" title="Thyroid Cartilage">TC</div>
          <div class="hotspot" style="left:50%;top:55%;color:var(--phon);background:var(--phon)" data-popup="hs-ph-2" title="Cricoid Cartilage">CC</div>
          <div class="hotspot" style="left:32%;top:38%;color:var(--phon);background:var(--phon)" data-popup="hs-ph-3" title="Vocal Folds">VF</div>
          <div class="hotspot" style="left:72%;top:38%;color:var(--phon);background:var(--phon)" data-popup="hs-ph-4" title="Arytenoids">AR</div>
          <div class="hotspot" style="left:50%;top:75%;color:var(--phon);background:var(--phon)" data-popup="hs-ph-5" title="Cricothyroid">CT</div>
        </div>
        <div class="hs-popup" id="hs-ph-1">
          <button class="pop-close" onclick="closePopup('hs-ph-1')">✕</button>
          <div class="pop-label"><span class="pop-accent" style="background:var(--phon)"></span>Laryngeal Cartilage</div>
          <h4>Thyroid Cartilage</h4>
          <p>The largest laryngeal cartilage. Two laminae fuse anteriorly to form the laryngeal prominence ("Adam's apple"), which is more prominent in males due to testosterone-driven growth. Provides anterior protection for the vocal folds. The superior and inferior cornua articulate with the hyoid bone and cricoid cartilage respectively.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="hs-popup" id="hs-ph-2">
          <button class="pop-close" onclick="closePopup('hs-ph-2')">✕</button>
          <div class="pop-label"><span class="pop-accent" style="background:var(--phon)"></span>Laryngeal Cartilage</div>
          <h4>Cricoid Cartilage</h4>
          <p>The only <strong>complete ring</strong> of cartilage in the entire airway — signet-ring shaped with a narrow anterior arch and broad posterior lamina. Supports the arytenoid cartilages on its superior surface. The <strong>cricothyroid joint</strong> allows the cricoid to rock/tilt, changing vocal fold length and tension to control pitch (F0).</p>
        </div>
        <div class="hs-popup" id="hs-ph-3">
          <button class="pop-close" onclick="closePopup('hs-ph-3')">✕</button>
          <div class="pop-label"><span class="pop-accent" style="background:var(--phon)"></span>Vibrating Structure</div>
          <h4>Vocal Folds</h4>
          <p>The true vocal folds span from the thyroid cartilage (anterior commissure) to the vocal processes of the arytenoids. They have a <strong>5-layer microstructure</strong> (Hirano, 1974): epithelium → superficial LP (Reinke's space — highly pliable, enables mucosal wave) → intermediate LP (elastic) → deep LP (collagen, forms vocal ligament) → thyroarytenoid/vocalis muscle (the "body"). The <strong>cover-body model</strong> explains differential stiffness during vibration.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="hs-popup" id="hs-ph-4">
          <button class="pop-close" onclick="closePopup('hs-ph-4')">✕</button>
          <div class="pop-label"><span class="pop-accent" style="background:var(--phon)"></span>Paired Cartilages</div>
          <h4>Arytenoid Cartilages</h4>
          <p>Paired pyramid-shaped cartilages sitting on the superior surface of the cricoid. The <strong>vocal processes</strong> provide posterior attachment for the vocal folds; the <strong>muscular processes</strong> are attachment sites for the PCA, LCA, and IA muscles. Movement of the arytenoids (rotation + gliding at the cricoarytenoid joint) opens and closes the glottis. <strong>PCA (posterior cricoarytenoid)</strong> is the ONLY abductor of the vocal folds.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="hs-popup" id="hs-ph-5">
          <button class="pop-close" onclick="closePopup('hs-ph-5')">✕</button>
          <div class="pop-label"><span class="pop-accent" style="background:var(--phon)"></span>Intrinsic Muscle</div>
          <h4>Cricothyroid Muscle (CT)</h4>
          <p>The primary <strong>pitch-raising</strong> muscle. When it contracts, it tilts the cricoid posteriorly relative to the thyroid (or tilts the thyroid forward), increasing the distance between the thyroid angle and the arytenoids — which <strong>lengthens and tenses the vocal folds</strong>, raising F0. It is the only intrinsic laryngeal muscle innervated by the <strong>superior laryngeal nerve (SLN/CN X)</strong> rather than the recurrent laryngeal nerve.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="diagram-caption">Fig. 5 — Laryngeal structures. Click hotspots to explore.</div>
        <div class="diagram-hint"><div class="pulse-dot-hint" style="--accent:var(--phon)"></div> Click the glowing circles to learn about each structure</div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="info-panel">
      <div class="info-intro">
        Vocal fold vibration is explained by the <strong>Myoelastic-Aerodynamic Theory</strong> (van den Berg, 1958): folds adduct → subglottal pressure builds → air forces folds open → Bernoulli effect + myoelastic recoil closes them → cycle repeats at F0.
      </div>
      <div class="accordion-item">
        <button class="accordion-btn" onclick="toggleAcc(this)">
          <span><span class="acc-label" style="background:rgba(139,38,53,.1);color:var(--phon)">Theory</span>Myoelastic-Aerodynamic Theory</span>
          <span class="acc-icon">▼</span>
        </button>
        <div class="accordion-body"><div class="accordion-body-inner"><ul>
          <li>1. LCA + IA + CT muscles <strong>adduct</strong> the vocal folds, closing the glottis</li>
          <li>2. Expired air builds <strong>subglottal pressure</strong> until it exceeds myoelastic closure force</li>
          <li>3. Air forces folds apart <strong>inferiorly first</strong>, creating the traveling mucosal wave</li>
          <li>4. <strong>Bernoulli effect:</strong> Air rushing through narrow glottis drops lateral pressure, sucking folds back together</li>
          <li>5. <strong>Myoelastic recoil</strong> + Bernoulli closes folds → cycle repeats at F0 (~120 Hz male, ~220 Hz female)</li>
        </ul></div></div>
      </div>
      <div class="accordion-item">
        <button class="accordion-btn" onclick="toggleAcc(this)">
          <span><span class="acc-label" style="background:rgba(139,38,53,.1);color:var(--phon)">Control</span>Pitch, Loudness &amp; Registers</span>
          <span class="acc-icon">▼</span>
        </button>
        <div class="accordion-body"><div class="accordion-body-inner"><ul>
          <li><strong>Raise pitch (F0):</strong> CT elongates/tenses folds → faster vibration</li>
          <li><strong>Lower pitch:</strong> TA (vocalis) shortens/thickens folds → slower vibration</li>
          <li><strong>Louder:</strong> Increase subglottal pressure (more respiratory force)</li>
          <li><strong>Modal register:</strong> Normal speech; full mucosal wave; complete open-close cycle</li>
          <li><strong>Falsetto:</strong> Thin elongated folds; high F0; possible incomplete closure</li>
          <li><strong>Pulse/vocal fry:</strong> Thick folds; very low F0 (~20–70 Hz); irregular, creaky vibration</li>
        </ul></div></div>
      </div>
      <a class="next-link" href="#resonatory" style="border-color:var(--reso);color:var(--reso)">
        <div><span class="nl-label">Next →</span>Resonatory System — the vocal tract shapes the sound</div>
        <span class="nl-arrow">→</span>
      </a>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- ══════════════════════════════════════
     06 — RESONATORY
══════════════════════════════════════ -->
<section id="resonatory" class="system-section sec-reso" style="background:var(--surface2)">
  <div class="sys-header">
    <div class="sys-step-tag">Step 06 · The Sound is Shaped</div>
    <h2 class="sys-title">Resonatory System</h2>
    <p class="sys-subtitle">The glottal source signal from the larynx passes into the vocal tract, where the pharyngeal, oral, and nasal cavities act as a resonance filter — shaping the acoustic signal into distinct vowels and voice quality (Source-Filter Theory, Fant, 1960).</p>
  </div>

  <div class="two-col flip">
    <div class="info-panel">
      <div class="info-intro">
        The vocal tract is ~17 cm long in adult males. It functions as an <strong>acoustic filter</strong> that selectively amplifies harmonics at <strong>formant frequencies (F1, F2, F3)</strong>. The configuration of the tract determines vowel identity and overall voice quality.
      </div>
      <div class="accordion-item">
        <button class="accordion-btn" onclick="toggleAcc(this)">
          <span><span class="acc-label" style="background:rgba(181,98,26,.1);color:var(--reso)">Theory</span>Source-Filter Theory (Fant, 1960)</span>
          <span class="acc-icon">▼</span>
        </button>
        <div class="accordion-body"><div class="accordion-body-inner"><ul>
          <li><strong>Source:</strong> Larynx produces complex periodic tone with F0 and harmonics (2F0, 3F0...)</li>
          <li><strong>Filter:</strong> Vocal tract selectively amplifies harmonics at formant frequencies</li>
          <li><strong>Output:</strong> Radiated speech signal at the lips</li>
          <li><strong>/a/ (father):</strong> High F1 (~800 Hz), Low F2 (~1,200 Hz) — jaw open, tongue low</li>
          <li><strong>/i/ (feet):</strong> Low F1 (~300 Hz), High F2 (~2,300 Hz) — jaw close, tongue front-high</li>
          <li><strong>/u/ (boot):</strong> Low F1, Low F2 — jaw close, tongue back-high</li>
        </ul></div></div>
      </div>
      <div class="accordion-item">
        <button class="accordion-btn" onclick="toggleAcc(this)">
          <span><span class="acc-label" style="background:rgba(181,98,26,.1);color:var(--reso)">Gate</span>Velopharyngeal Mechanism</span>
          <span class="acc-icon">▼</span>
        </button>
        <div class="accordion-body"><div class="accordion-body-inner"><ul>
          <li><strong>Velum elevates:</strong> VP port closes → oral resonance (most sounds)</li>
          <li><strong>Velum lowers:</strong> VP port opens → nasal coupling for /m/, /n/, /ŋ/</li>
          <li><strong>Levator veli palatini (CN X):</strong> Primary velar elevator</li>
          <li><strong>Tensor veli palatini (CN V):</strong> Tenses velum; opens Eustachian tube</li>
          <li><strong>Velopharyngeal insufficiency (VPI):</strong> Incomplete closure → hypernasality</li>
        </ul></div></div>
      </div>
      <a class="next-link" href="#articulatory" style="border-color:var(--arti);color:var(--arti)">
        <div><span class="nl-label">Next →</span>Articulatory System — the phonemes are formed</div>
        <span class="nl-arrow">→</span>
      </a>
    </div>
    <div>
      <div class="diagram-wrap">
        <div class="diagram-img-area">
          <div class="diagram-placeholder">
            <div style="font-size:2.5rem">🔊</div>
            <strong style="font-size:.8rem">REPLACE WITH YOUR IMAGE</strong>
            <span>Suggested: Midsagittal view of vocal tract<br/>showing pharyngeal, oral, nasal cavities</span>
          </div>
          <div class="hotspot" style="left:50%;top:20%;color:var(--reso);background:var(--reso)" data-popup="hs-rs-1" title="Nasal Cavity">NC</div>
          <div class="hotspot" style="left:65%;top:45%;color:var(--reso);background:var(--reso)" data-popup="hs-rs-2" title="Oral Cavity">OC</div>
          <div class="hotspot" style="left:35%;top:55%;color:var(--reso);background:var(--reso)" data-popup="hs-rs-3" title="Pharyngeal Cavity">PC</div>
          <div class="hotspot" style="left:58%;top:35%;color:var(--reso);background:var(--reso)" data-popup="hs-rs-4" title="Velum">VP</div>
        </div>
        <div class="hs-popup" id="hs-rs-1">
          <button class="pop-close" onclick="closePopup('hs-rs-1')">✕</button>
          <div class="pop-label"><span class="pop-accent" style="background:var(--reso)"></span>Resonating Cavity</div>
          <h4>Nasal Cavity</h4>
          <p>Coupled to the vocal tract when the velum is lowered for nasal consonants (/m/, /n/, /ŋ/). Adds nasal resonance quality. The paranasal sinuses contribute minimally to resonance. When saying "Yes" in response to "Do you like cheese?", the /n/ in "cheese" requires brief velar lowering to couple the nasal cavity.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="hs-popup" id="hs-rs-2">
          <button class="pop-close" onclick="closePopup('hs-rs-2')">✕</button>
          <div class="pop-label"><span class="pop-accent" style="background:var(--reso)"></span>Resonating Cavity</div>
          <h4>Oral Cavity</h4>
          <p>The shape of the oral cavity primarily determines <strong>F1 and F2</strong> (the two formants that encode vowel identity). Configuration is set by tongue height and front-back position, jaw opening, and lip posture. Jaw opening drives F1 (open jaw = higher F1); tongue front-back position drives F2 (front tongue = higher F2).</p>
        </div>
        <div class="hs-popup" id="hs-rs-3">
          <button class="pop-close" onclick="closePopup('hs-rs-3')">✕</button>
          <div class="pop-label"><span class="pop-accent" style="background:var(--reso)"></span>Resonating Cavity</div>
          <h4>Pharyngeal Cavity</h4>
          <p>Extending from the laryngopharynx to the nasopharynx, the pharynx is the primary resonating tube of the vocal tract. Its shape is altered by <strong>larynx height</strong> (raised larynx = shorter, higher-resonance pharynx), <strong>tongue root position</strong> (advanced vs. retracted), and the <strong>pharyngeal constrictor muscles</strong>. Changes in pharyngeal shape alter all formant frequencies.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="hs-popup" id="hs-rs-4">
          <button class="pop-close" onclick="closePopup('hs-rs-4')">✕</button>
          <div class="pop-label"><span class="pop-accent" style="background:var(--reso)"></span>VP Valve</div>
          <h4>Velum &amp; Velopharyngeal Port</h4>
          <p>The soft palate (velum) is the critical valve controlling nasal/oral resonance coupling. Elevated by the <strong>levator veli palatini (CN X)</strong> for oral sounds; lowered by gravity and <strong>palatoglossus</strong> for nasal sounds. The velopharyngeal port must close completely for all non-nasal sounds to prevent hypernasality. This is assessed clinically via nasendoscopy.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="diagram-caption">Fig. 6 — Vocal tract resonating cavities. Click hotspots to explore.</div>
        <div class="diagram-hint"><div class="pulse-dot-hint" style="--accent:var(--reso)"></div> Click the glowing circles to learn about each cavity</div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

