<section id="articulatory" class="system-section sec-arti">
  <div class="sys-header">
    <div class="sys-step-tag">Step 07 · The Words Are Formed</div>
    <h2 class="sys-title">Articulatory System</h2>
    <p class="sys-subtitle">The final step — the tongue, lips, jaw, and teeth shape the resonated acoustic signal into the precise phonemes of the spoken response. Each phoneme requires a specific articulatory configuration, executed within milliseconds.</p>
  </div>

  <div class="two-col">
    <div>
      <div class="diagram-wrap">
        <div class="diagram-img-area">
          <div class="diagram-placeholder">
            <div style="font-size:2.5rem">👄</div>
            <strong style="font-size:.8rem">REPLACE WITH YOUR IMAGE</strong>
            <span>Suggested: Midsagittal view showing tongue,<br/>lips, teeth, hard palate, alveolar ridge</span>
          </div>
          <div class="hotspot" style="left:55%;top:35%;color:var(--arti);background:var(--arti)" data-popup="hs-at-1" title="Tongue">TG</div>
          <div class="hotspot" style="left:78%;top:55%;color:var(--arti);background:var(--arti)" data-popup="hs-at-2" title="Lips">LP</div>
          <div class="hotspot" style="left:55%;top:18%;color:var(--arti);background:var(--arti)" data-popup="hs-at-3" title="Hard Palate">HP</div>
          <div class="hotspot" style="left:68%;top:25%;color:var(--arti);background:var(--arti)" data-popup="hs-at-4" title="Alveolar Ridge">AR</div>
          <div class="hotspot" style="left:72%;top:68%;color:var(--arti);background:var(--arti)" data-popup="hs-at-5" title="Mandible / Jaw">JW</div>
        </div>
        <div class="hs-popup" id="hs-at-1">
          <button class="pop-close" onclick="closePopup('hs-at-1')">✕</button>
          <div class="pop-label"><span class="pop-accent" style="background:var(--arti)"></span>Primary Articulator</div>
          <h4>Tongue</h4>
          <p>A muscular hydrostat — maintains constant volume while changing shape. <strong>Intrinsic muscles (CN XII)</strong> change shape: superior longitudinal (curls tip up), inferior longitudinal (curls tip down), transverse (narrows + elongates), vertical (flattens + widens). <strong>Extrinsic muscles (CN XII)</strong> change position: genioglossus (protrusion — largest), hyoglossus (depress + retract), styloglossus (retract + elevate). Exception: palatoglossus = CN X.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="hs-popup" id="hs-at-2">
          <button class="pop-close" onclick="closePopup('hs-at-2')">✕</button>
          <div class="pop-label"><span class="pop-accent" style="background:var(--arti)"></span>Active Articulator (CN VII)</div>
          <h4>Lips</h4>
          <p><strong>Orbicularis oris:</strong> Closes and purses the lips — essential for bilabial sounds (/p/, /b/, /m/) and rounded vowels. <strong>Buccinator:</strong> Compresses cheeks; keeps air in the oral cavity. <strong>Zygomaticus major:</strong> Retracts lip corners for lip spreading (/i/). <strong>Depressor labii:</strong> Lowers lower lip for labiodentals. All lip muscles are innervated by <strong>CN VII (Facial)</strong>.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="hs-popup" id="hs-at-3">
          <button class="pop-close" onclick="closePopup('hs-at-3')">✕</button>
          <div class="pop-label"><span class="pop-accent" style="background:var(--arti)"></span>Passive Articulator</div>
          <h4>Hard Palate</h4>
          <p>The bony roof of the mouth, formed by the <strong>maxilla</strong> (anterior palatine process) and <strong>palatine bones</strong> (posterior). A passive articulator — it doesn't move, but serves as the target for palatal sounds: /ʃ/ (she), /ʒ/ (measure), /tʃ/ (cheese), /dʒ/ (judge). The word "cheese" in our target phrase requires the tongue to contact the hard palate for the /tʃ/ affricate.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="hs-popup" id="hs-at-4">
          <button class="pop-close" onclick="closePopup('hs-at-4')">✕</button>
          <div class="pop-label"><span class="pop-accent" style="background:var(--arti)"></span>Passive Articulator</div>
          <h4>Alveolar Ridge</h4>
          <p>The bony ridge immediately posterior to the upper incisors. The most frequently used passive articulation target in English — the tongue tip or blade makes contact or approximation here for: /t/, /d/, /n/, /s/, /z/, /l/, /r/. In saying "Yes" (/j-ɛ-s/), the /s/ requires precise tongue-alveolar approximation to generate the high-frequency turbulence characteristic of sibilants.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="hs-popup" id="hs-at-5">
          <button class="pop-close" onclick="closePopup('hs-at-5')">✕</button>
          <div class="pop-label"><span class="pop-accent" style="background:var(--arti)"></span>Active Articulator (CN V)</div>
          <h4>Mandible / Jaw</h4>
          <p>The only moveable bone of the skull. Jaw height directly determines <strong>vowel F1 frequency</strong> (open jaw = higher F1). Key muscles: <strong>masseter</strong> (elevates jaw — strongest closer), <strong>temporalis</strong> (elevates + retracts), <strong>medial pterygoid</strong> (elevation), <strong>lateral pterygoid</strong> (opens jaw, protrudes mandible). All innervated by <strong>CN V (Trigeminal)</strong>.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="diagram-caption">Fig. 7 — Articulatory structures. Click hotspots to explore.</div>
        <div class="diagram-hint"><div class="pulse-dot-hint" style="--accent:var(--arti)"></div> Click the glowing circles to learn about each structure</div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="info-panel">
      <div class="info-intro">
        Articulation involves <strong>active articulators</strong> (tongue, lips, jaw — they move) and <strong>passive articulators</strong> (alveolar ridge, hard palate, teeth — stationary targets). The sound wave radiating from the lips is the final product of all seven systems working in concert.
      </div>
      <div class="accordion-item">
        <button class="accordion-btn" onclick="toggleAcc(this)">
          <span><span class="acc-label" style="background:rgba(74,103,65,.1);color:var(--arti)">Theory</span>Theories of Articulation</span>
          <span class="acc-icon">▼</span>
        </button>
        <div class="accordion-body"><div class="accordion-body-inner"><ul>
          <li><strong>Motor Theory (Liberman et al., 1967):</strong> Listeners perceive speech by mentally simulating the articulatory gestures that produced it</li>
          <li><strong>Acoustic Theory:</strong> Listeners decode acoustic cues directly, without reference to articulatory gestures</li>
          <li><strong>Task Dynamic/Articulatory Phonology (Browman &amp; Goldstein):</strong> Speech units are coordinative structures — overlapping articulatory gestures, not discrete sequential segments</li>
        </ul></div></div>
      </div>
      <div class="accordion-item">
        <button class="accordion-btn" onclick="toggleAcc(this)">
          <span><span class="acc-label" style="background:rgba(74,103,65,.1);color:var(--arti)">Example</span>"Yes, I love cheese!" — Articulation Breakdown</span>
          <span class="acc-icon">▼</span>
        </button>
        <div class="accordion-body"><div class="accordion-body-inner"><ul>
          <li><strong>/j/ (yes):</strong> Tongue body high and front, approximates hard palate</li>
          <li><strong>/ɛ/ (yes):</strong> Jaw moderately open, tongue mid-front — F1 mid, F2 high</li>
          <li><strong>/s/ (yes):</strong> Tongue tip near alveolar ridge; narrow constriction creates high-frequency turbulence</li>
          <li><strong>/l/ (love):</strong> Tongue tip on alveolar ridge; lateral airflow around sides of tongue</li>
          <li><strong>/tʃ/ (cheese):</strong> Tongue blade contacts hard palate (stop phase) → releases to palatal fricative</li>
          <li><strong>/z/ (cheese):</strong> Like /s/ but with vocal fold adduction for voicing</li>
        </ul></div></div>
      </div>
      <div style="background:var(--surface2);border:1px solid var(--rule);border-radius:10px;padding:1rem 1.2rem;margin-top:.5rem;font-size:.82rem;line-height:1.7;color:#555">
        🎉 <strong style="color:var(--ink)">The speech chain is complete.</strong> The acoustic signal leaves the lips, travels through the air, and reaches the next listener's ear — where the entire process begins again.
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

